points to note:
1. the browser never sees the unhashed nonce, and so cannot redeem the AC (this
is the point of PKCE)
2. the browser never sees the backend's client_secret, and so cannot generate
and redeem its own nonce (this is Authorization Code Flow)
3. the nonce means that eavesdroppers of step 5 or 6 (a common problem on
mobile) can't redeem the AC as they don't know the unhashed nonce
4. the JWT (access token) returned in step 8 is not seen by the browser and so
can't be stolen by client-side attacks (this is a major feature of
Authorization Code Flow)
Description of process:
0. The backend developer registers or obtains a client_secret (red diamond) from
the OAuth provider, and stores it in their backend. This is like a password
that the backend uses to prove to the Oauth provider that it is really the
app that is asking for access. This password is only ever sent to the OAuth
provider, never through the browser.
1. The backend generates a random string (the "nonce"). It saves the nonce for
later. (green oval). This is the "Proof Key".
2. The backend causes the browser to redirect to the Oauth provider's
authorization endpoint, and provides a hash of the "nonce" (checked oval).
3. The browser sends the hash of the "nonce" to the Oauth provider, which it
keeps for later.
4. The OAuth provider asks the user if they want to grant access, and then
generates a new Authorization Code (the "AC"). It saves the AC with the
hashed nonce. The AC and nonce can only be used once (to prevent replay
attacks).
5. The OAuth provider redirects the user back to the webapp. This is the part
that can get hijacked and leak the AC. Without the nonce, however, there's no
point.
6. The webapp's frontend (the browser) sends the AC to the backend. This is
usually the `/oauth/token` endpoint. This is the step that often gets
hijacked on mobiles, when the "browser" is actually another app and a
malicious app registers as the "url handler" for the backend.
7. The backend can finally redeem the AC for an access token (blue rectangle).
The Oauth provider checks the client_secret to make sure the backend is who
they say they are, and also makes sure that the provided nonce hashes to the
stored hash that is associated with the AC.
8. If the backend is who they say they are, and the nonce hashes to the stored
nonce, then the backend finally gets its access token.
9. The backend can then use the permissions the user has granted in step 3/4/5
to make requests to another service.
10. The other service checks the JWT signature to make sure the contents are
approved by the OAuth provider (and thus that the user has granted
permissions).
Why?
This flow is about letting the user grant some permissions to the webapp for
talking to another service. For example, your webapp might want to read your
Gmail contacts, but you don't want to give the webapp your Google password. So
instead, the webapp can get an Access Token with certain permissions that it can
talk to Gmail with.
The next problem is that browsers often let Access Tokens get stolen (thorugh
URLs or Javascript), so we don't want to send it through there. Instead, we will
use the browser to request an Authorization Code. This is where the Oauth
provider (Google in our example) makes sure the user is OK with granting access.
Then, the backend can obtain the Access Token directly from the Oauth provider
(without going through the browser).
We also add a client_secret to make sure that no-one else can pretend to be our
webapp backend.
Unfortunately, the Authorization Code is almost as good as an Access Token, as
anyone can send it to the backend and get granted access. So we add the PKCE
"pixie" nonce as well, as explained above.
